TY  - JOUR
T1  - Emotional Exhaustion in a High Stress Organization
AU  - Gaines, Jeannie
AU  - Jermier, John M.
Y1  - 1983/12/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255907
DO  - 10.5465/255907
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 567
EP  - 586
VL  - 26
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study develops the concept of emotional exhaustion, an extremely affective and chronic type of work-related strain. Sources of emotional exhaustion were investigated in a police organization that was struggling with major changes. The findings suggest that emotional exhaustion is partially the result of personal characteristics of the employee, interpersonal milieu, and the work itself, but is profoundly affected by departmental context, administrative policy and practices, and the contradictory mandate of police in society.
AB  - This study develops the concept of emotional exhaustion, an extremely affective and chronic type of work-related strain. Sources of emotional exhaustion were investigated in a police organization that was struggling with major changes. The findings suggest that emotional exhaustion is partially the result of personal characteristics of the employee, interpersonal milieu, and the work itself, but is profoundly affected by departmental context, administrative policy and practices, and the contradictory mandate of police in society.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255907
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255907
Y2  - 2026/04/24
